<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-034-596  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 034 596.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  Jan 8 1990 v36 n1791 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>No recession, but industry braces for a 'pause' through firsthalf. (sales in electronics industry to be slow through first halfof 1990)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Sales in the electronics industry will remain slow through thefirst half of 1990, say analysts, continuing the depressed marketfirst experienced in the last months of 1989.andP;  Factors includingovercapacity and price erosion in the computer and semiconductorsegments, an expected drop in defense spending and lower capitalexpenditures will contribute to the slow sales, but a recession isnot expected to result.andP;  Commodity markets, such as DRAMs,microcomputers and passive components, are hardest hit by theslowdown, while hardware sales continue to grow.andP;  Semiconductorproduction and test equipment sales are expected to be bolsteredby export sales.andP;  The Electronics Industries Assn predicts thatthe 5.5 percent growth factor of 1989 will slow to three percentin 1990.andP;  The Aerospace Industries Assn likewise expects adecline.andP;  The design automation segment of the industry isexpected to be insulated from declines.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ElectronicsSalesMarket Analysis.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   U.S. factory sales, 1986 - 1990. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>